    <title>Google and the DOJ make their final arguments in the ad tech monopoly case</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="Photo collage of a page full of ads for different products with the Google Ads logo." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/ipAK3ATNltUlC9W1VOsoobT3UZY=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73747431/STK445_ADVERTISING_STK093_GOOGLE_B.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Image: Cath Virginia / The Verge, Getty Images&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="5ZqD5R"&gt;Google and the Department of Justice met one final time in an Alexandria, Virginia courtroom to debate the future of Google’s online ad tech juggernaut.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="PUhERp"&gt;Over about three hours of closing arguments, attorneys for each side&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;delivered their last arguments before US District Court judge Leonie Brinkema, who is expected to rule on it by the end of 2024. If she declares Google’s ad tech system a monopoly, the case will progress to a second trial for remedies — a process currently &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/10/9/24265983/doj-google-search-remedies-monopoly"&gt;playing out in a separate DC District Court case over Google search.&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="PdHOrU"&gt;Many of the arguments were familiar to any Google trial watcher. The DOJ argues Google used a suite of ad tech products, particularly Doubleclick For Publishers (DFP) and the AdX exchange, to &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/9/11/24241386/former-news-corp-executive-google-doj-ad-tech-trial"&gt;s...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
